- takes responsibility seriously.\n- regarded as a know-it-all.\n- has a hot temper.\n\nNo mention of stress handling, crew atmosphere, etc.\n\nThus we must adjust our public message: remove references to stress handling and crew atmosphere for C. Also remove any inference that C creates positive atmosphere. Also we must not claim any attribute not present.\n\nWe can still note that C is very conscientious, understands tech, quick decision making, but has communication difficulty, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nWe can still ask about any missing info for A's calmness, D's teamwork, B's teamwork.\n\nWe need to adjust the assessment accordingly.\n\nNow we need to produce final public message with corrected reasoning and vote. Which candidate is best? Let's re-evaluate with corrected data.\n\nCandidate A: strong technical, leadership, but show-off, not open to new ideas. No info on calmness, reliability, teamwork communication.\n\nCandidate B: calm in crisis, 100% reliable, good weather assessment, computer skills, but weak memory for numbers, nasty remarks (bad teamwork). No explicit teamwork positive.\n\nCandidate C: quick correct decisions, very conscientious, understands complicated technology, but difficulty communicating, egocentric, not willing to further education. No explicit teamwork positive.\n\nCandidate D: responds adequately to unexpected events, concentration, problem solving, responsibility, but know-it-all, hot temper. No explicit teamwork.\n\nThus all have some negatives. Which is best? For long-distance pilot, reliability and calmness are crucial. B is 100% reliable and calm in crisis. That is strong. However B's nasty remarks about colleagues is a serious teamwork issue. But maybe we can weigh reliability and calmness higher. C is conscientious and quick decision making, but communication difficulty and egocentric may be problematic. A has leadership but show-off and not open to new ideas. D has hot temper.\n\nGiven the data, B's r